ous (including the Empire Windrush in 1948) to the obscure, such as the Volga German transmigrants passing through Britain in the 1870s. While employing a broadly historical approach, Kushner incorporates insights from many other disciplines and employs a comparative methodology to highlight the importance of the symbolic as well as the physical nature of such journeys.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aImmigrantszGreat BritainxHistory. 4amanchesterhive variable pricing textbooks. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aBritain.  aEmpire Windrush.  aHuguenot refugees.  aVolga German transmigrants.  aasylum seekers.  aeast European workers.  amigrant journeys.1 aKushner, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez9783111283630oZDB-23-MUP40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526130389423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526130389/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-MUPc1986d2013